    "title": "Pregnant women in WA's Kimberley face big distances to hospital and high rates of heart condition, diabetes",
    "content": "Darlene Cox says it can be difficult having to give birth so far away from home. ( ABC Kimberley: Ruby Littler )\nMedical practitioners say there are high rates of rheumatic heart disease and diabetes among pregnant women in Western Australia's far north.\nPregnant women are enduring financial strain, long travel distances and emotional stress to receive basic prenatal services.\nThe Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists is conducting remote training courses to upskill healthcare staff.\nFor expectant mothers living across Western Australia's vast remote north, getting to the nearest hospital is not always straightforward.\nFar from having a go-bag ready for when contractions start, pregnant women living in towns across the Kimberley are often expected to relocate weeks, if not months, before they are due to give birth.\nThe tyranny of distance hits close to home for Darlene Cox, from Noonkanbah, a 5.5-hour, 380-kilometre drive from the main hospital offering maternity care in Broome.\nAdding to the challenges facing both expectant mums and their obstetrics carers is the greater number of moderate-to-high-risk pregnancies.\nA mobile ultrasound unit, which can travel to remote communities, has been suggested as a possible solution. ( ABC Kimberley: Ruby Littler )\nThese are driven by high rates of preventable conditions across the Kimberley, including potentially fatal rheumatic heart disease, and diabetes, which disproportionately affects First Nations women.\nKimberley obstetricians and midwives say this is largely due to social and environmental factors and the difficulties in detecting and diagnosing conditions early in remote Indigenous communities.\nMs Cox, who is diabetic, has been staying in motels and Aboriginal Short Stay accommodation in Broome for the past two months.\nDarlene Cox has been receiving prenatal care in Broome and is considered to be at higher risk due to her diabetes. ( ABC Kimberley: Ruby Littler )\n\"It is a challenge being away from your community, especially where you grew up and lived for that long, not seeing family and friends' faces,\" Ms Cox said.\nMs Cox said the hundreds of kilometres of travel was getting too difficult to manage.",
