    "title": "Advocates call for more genetic screening for disease risks as young people say 'knowledge is power'",
    "content": "Ben Neat discovered through a genetic screening survey that he had a higher risk of developing certain types of cancers. ( Supplied )\nWhen Ben Neat heard about a genetic screening study that Monash University was conducting, he thought it might be a good opportunity to fill in gaps in his medical history.\n\"There's a bit of an adoption background in my family,\" Mr Neat told triple j hack.\nThere weren't any illnesses in his immediate family that raised red flags for him. So when the results came back showing Mr Neat carried the gene mutation PALB2 — a variant that increased his risk of certain cancers — he was shocked.\nThe Monash University study tested 10,000 people aged between 18 and 40 for genetic variants that could lead to an elevated risk of some cancers and heart problems.\n\"We focused on really high-risk conditions that were medically actionable and that means there's something that you can do to either prevent it or catch it early and treat it at a really early stage if you know you have risk,\" co-lead of the DNA Screen study, Jane Tiller, told triple j hack.\nThe study found 2 per cent of participants, or one in 50 young people, carried a genetic variant, which Dr Tiller said was \"a shade more than\" researchers had expected.\nMonika Tobin was among the 2 per cent of participants who had an adverse genetic result.\n\"I found out that I have the LDLR variant, which means I have hypercholesterolaemia,\" Ms Tobin told triple j hack.\nMonika Tobin (centre) found out she had a genetic cholesterol issue that could lead to heart problems. ( Supplied: Irene Dowdy )\nThe genetic variant means Ms Tobin has a much higher risk of heart problems as she ages.\n\"My body doesn't process cholesterol in the same way and it's something that I'm born with, so it means I have higher levels of cholesterol than other people,\" she said.\nThe results came as a shock to Ms Tobin, who had a nine-month-old daughter at the time.\nThe results prompted some difficult conversations for Mr Neat, especially with female family members who, if they carry the PALB2 variant, are up to 55 per cent more likely to develop breast cancer.\n\"I had to sit down at the dinner table and tell mum and dad that I had a higher risk of cancer. I had to sit down with my sister and ask her to get tested,\" he said.",
