    "content": "Victor Harbor woman Bek Batt is waiting on heart surgery at Flinders Medical Centre. ( ABC News )\nA woman waiting for heart surgery at an Adelaide hospital says she has fears she may die before she receives the treatment she needs.\nAfter the ABC made inquiries with SA Health, the woman was informed her surgery would take place next week.\nThe local health network boss has apologised to the patient for the delay.\nA South Australian woman who feared she might not make it while waiting for heart surgery has been told her life-saving procedure has been scheduled for next week.\nBek Batt told ABC Radio Adelaide on Tuesday morning that she was told in January that she needed a pacemaker and two stents in her heart, as well as a cardiac ablation, to treat an irregular heartbeat.\nThe Victor Harbor woman said she had met a surgeon and was told she would be waiting for no more than a month.\n\"He said if he had his way I'd be in within two weeks, I was promised it would be no more than two weeks, no more than four weeks, I'm still waiting,\" she said.\n\"I think I'll be gone before I get the heart surgery.\"\nThe Flinders Medical Centre is one of the busiest hospitals in Adelaide. ( ABC News: Che Chorley )\nThe 60-year-old woman said she was worried she would have a stroke while waiting for the surgery at Flinders Medical Centre (FMC) after already waiting 18 months for the specialist appointment.\nBut she said she understood the significant demand on healthcare workers.\n\"They're all under pressure and there's no way around it,\" Ms Batt said.\n\"It's a real juggling system for everybody, I understand it … but it's difficult just sitting in limbo.\"\nAfter speaking with the ABC, Ms Batt was told her surgery had been scheduled for next week.",
